Trim the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways and thinly slice.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}.

Roughly chop the @walnuts{20} and set aside.

Trim and chop the @green beans{80} into thirds.

Pour the @water{750}(for the stock) into a medium #saucepan{} on high heat.

Add the @mushroom broth paste{15%g} and @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, then stir to combine. Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to the lowest setting.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the @sliced mushrooms{120%g} and leek and stir-fry until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Stir the garlic into frying pan and cook, stirring frequently, for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @risotto rice{175%g}, then stir and cook until the edges of the rice are translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir a ladle of your stock into the rice. When the stock has been absorbed by the rice, stir in another ladle of stock.

Keep the pan on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time.

The cooking time should take ~{20-25%minutes} and your risotto is done when your rice is 'al dente' - cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

When the risotto has 5 mins of cooking time left, stir in the green beans and cook for the remaining time until just tender. Add a splash of @?water{splash} if you feel it needs it.

Once cooked, remove the risotto from the heat. Stir in some @?butter{}, a squeeze of lemon juice, the walnuts and three quarters of the @hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated). Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Serve your risotto in deep #bowls{} sprinkled with the lemon zest and the remaining hard Italian style cheese. Enjoy!

> This delicious Stovetop Mushroom & Leek Risotto has been expertly designed as a lighter option to help with a balanced lifestyle.